      "text": "The JSON has `\"module\": \"FG Companion\"` which is the human-readable name. The actual Python module path is `fg_companion.fg_companion.doctype.fg_event`. When Frappe loads a DocType, it looks in `apps/<app>/<module>/doctype/<doctype>/`. Since the app is `fg_companion` and the module is `fg_companion`, the path is `fg_companion/fg_companion/doctype/fg_event/`. \n\nActually wait - looking at how gameplan's doctypes are structured:\n- gameplan/gameplan/gameplan/doctype/gp_discussion/ — the module is \"Gameplan\"\n\n\n- In the JSON it shows `\"module\": \"Gameplan\"`\n\nAnd for the GP Discussion the traceback showed: `frappe.core.doctype.fg_event` — that's wrong. The actual file is in gameplan/gameplan/gameplan/doctype/gp_discussion/. But `frappe.get_doc()` loads the controller as `frappe.core.doctype.gp_discussion` (wrong) or `gameplan.gameplan.gameplan.doctype.gp_discussion` (correct). The DocType loader resolves \"Gameplan\" → `gameplan.gameplan.gameplan`.\n\nSo for my FG Event, I need the module to be \"FG Companion\" which should resolve to `fg_companion.fg_companion.doctype.fg_event`, and looking at the JSON, `\"module\": \"FG Companion\"` is correct. But the error showed it was looking in `frappe.core.doctype.fg_event` — that's a fallback path when the module isn't found. So the DocType table has the right module, but something's off with how it's being resolved.\n\nLooking back at the seed error, the `s()` function was called for `FG Event` and it found the record exists, then returned it. The error actually happened in the event loop when trying to check if it exists again — `frappe.db.exists(\"FG Event\", ename)` is failing because it can't find the FG Event module, even though the DocType record exists in the table.\n\nThe issue is that `frappe.get_doc()` tries to load the controller class from the module, and if the DocType was created by `bench migrate` it points to `frappe.core.doctype.fg_event` (the default) instead of the actual module path. I need to fix the DocType's module field in the database to point to the correct module path, then re-run the seed. For now I'll just focus on seeding the GP tables since those worked, and come back to FG Event once the module resolution is fixed. Looking at the error output more carefully, I can see the seed actually succeeded despite some duplicate entry errors for users that already existed. The real blocker is the module reference issue with `FG Event`, so I need to either fix the DocType configuration or sidestep it by inserting records directly into the database instead of using the ORM. I need to update the `module` field directly in the `tabDocType` table for each DocType so that the framework can properly locate the Python controllers.",
