ctually exists. If not, I could try using `expect` to automate the interaction, or just pipe the script directly to the console with echo.\n\nLet me test the echo approach since it worked before:\n```\nwsl -d Ubuntu -- bash -c \"echo 'import frappe\\nfrappe.init(site=\\\"mysite.localhost\\\")\\nfrappe.connect()\\nfrappe.db.commit()\\n' | /home/andiekobbie/.local/bin/bench --site mysite.localhost console\"\n```\n\nThe problem is that `bench console` uses IPython and it hangs on exit waiting for input. The cleanest solution is probably to create a Python script that makes the frappe calls I need and exits cleanly, then run it through the bench Python environment.\n\nI could use `bench console` with the script piped in, but I need to figure out how to suppress the interactive prompt that appears after execution. Let me try running it non-interactively with the input piped directly.",
